history.provenance: Based on the note C XV on , a former librarian believes that the manuscript may have belonged to King Charles XV of Sweden and Norway. The signa 140 on and 324 on the have not been identified.

msItem.explicit: dirigendos pedes nostros in viam pacis deus israhel
msItem.note: Invitatories, antiphons, psalms, hymns, and verses for the weekly cycle of Lauds; for Monday and Tuesday, also chapter. The hymns are given in full; the other items by incipit only.

supportDesc.condition: The edges have been trimmed with loss of some of the text of the marginal notations. The two bifolia making up / and / respectively have been placed in the wrong order and should switch places. A dummy-quire of 12 leaves has been inserted after for support.

Beginning at Ps 1 and continuing until Ps 147, a contemporary hand has added the antiphons, and occasionally also versicles and responsories (e.g. , ), for the psalms in the margin, using rubrics in red and with capitals touched in red. The incipit of the antiphon precedes the psalm or psalms it belongs to and the full antiphon is given at the end of the psalm or sequence of psalms. In several instances, the writing of the first hand has been erased and a second medieval hand has added a different antiphon on top of the erasure, e.g. and .
Psalm numbers according to the Hebrew numbering in ink in the margin by an early modern hand. Starting at (Ps 11), Gallican (Vulgate) numbers in pencil below, in parentheses.

decoDesc.p: Main text in dark ink; rubrics in red.
decoDesc.decoNote: : KL over 3 lines in blue and red at head of each month. The most elaborate decoration scheme of the psalm initials corresponds to the traditional division of the psalms into three groups of 50, Pss 1-50, Pss 51-100, and Pss 101-150. The less elaborate decoration scheme corresponds to the secular cursus, with larger, decorated initials at Ps. 1, 26, 38, 52, 68, 80, 97, 109. The exception is Ps. 52, which is decorated according to the more elaborate scheme. (Ps. 1): foliate opening initial B over 9 lines inside a purple frame with a black outline; letter body made up of a vine stem pattern in blue, green and red, with foliage in blue, red and green; counter space in gold. (Ps. 51): foliate initial Q over 5 lines inside a black frame with a green background; letter body made up of a vine stem pattern in blue, red and purple, with foliage in blue, red and green; counter space in gold. (Ps. 52): foliate initial D over 4 lines inside a black frame with a background in gold; letter body in blue with foliage in blue and green; in the counter space, a red flower with green leaves on a black background. (Ps. 97): foliate initial C over 4 lines inside a black frame with a background in purple and gold; letter body in blue with foliage in blue, red and green. (Ps. 101): foliate initial D over 5 lines inside a black frame on a green background; letter body made up of a vine stem pattern in blue, red, and purple with foliage in blue, green, red, and gold; counter space in gold. (Ps. 26), (Ps 38), (Ps. 68), (Ps. 80), (Ps. 109): puzzle psalm initials over 5 lines in red and blue and counter space filled with penwork in red and blue. , : plain psalm or item initials over 2 lines alternating in red and blue, ascenders/descenders extending into the margin. : plain initials over 1 line alternating in red and blue. For further description of the decoration see Lindqvist Sandgren.
